Agor Cyclotron at the KVI,Groningen.
The stacked foil technique is employed to
simultaneously bombard 232-Th, 208-Pb, nat-Pb, 197-Au
and nat-W targets.
And monitor foil.
Irradiation beam current - 10 nano-A.
Two irradiations, one of 5 minutes and one of 2 hours.
The stacked foil of Th-232, Pb-208, Pb-nat, Au-197 and
W-nat were used.
For the measurements of longer-lived fission isotopes,
each individual target foil is sandwiched between first
a thin approx. 0.3 mg/cm**2 and then a thicker approx.
3 mg/cm**2 Mylar foil. The thin foil acts as a filter,
the thick Mylar foils trap all fragments which pass the
thin ones. After activation they taken from the stack
and used for further analysis as samples free from
evaporation products.
For the measurements of short-lived isotopes was used a
catcher cylinder, made of polyethylene. A cylinder
allows the protons to pass without hitting the catcher
itself. The catcher cylinder wall (approx. 4 mg/cm**2)
has full stopping power for all the fission fragments.
Efficiency of fission fragment collection was
calculated by Monte-Carlo Method.
